1.(c). It does not matter for this particular polynomial and data points it is fitting. The polynomial fits the four data points perfectly. The residuals are all 0. Thus, this polynomial would have 0 total loss for any other loss function (since any combination of 0's is 0).

#(e) MSE
mse_residuals = []
constant_y = np.linspace(-10, 20, 100)
for each in constant_y:
    mse_residuals.append(np.sum((np.full(n_samples, each) - new_y)**2) / len(new_x))
mse_residuals = np.array(mse_residuals)

print('denoting the mean point using the black line')
plt.plot(constant_y, mse_residuals, color='green')

plt.ylabel("MSE")

#(e) Special Loss function(slf)
slf_residuals = []
for each in constant_y:
  residuals = new_y - np.full(n_samples, each) 
  slf_total_loss = 0.0
  
  for res_i, x_i in zip(residuals, new_x):
    if res_i < 0:
      l_res_i = -0.2*res_i
    else:
      l_res_i = 10*res_i

    l_res_i = l_res_i/(abs(x_i - 5)+0.01)

    slf_total_loss = slf_total_loss + l_res_i

  slf_residuals.append(slf_total_loss)
  
slf_residuals = np.array(slf_residuals)

plt.plot(constant_y, slf_residuals, color='green')
plt.xlabel("a0")
plt.ylabel("SLF")
plt.show()

1.(f) i. the loss function prefers over-estimating. Eg, using $a_0=20$ is above all/most of the data points, so the residuals are negative and not as heavily penalized as under-predicting (e.g. $a_0 = -5$)

ii. The loss function is more sensitive to the fit around $x=5$. If a sample has an $x$ value around $5$, the fraction $$\frac{1}{|x - 5|+0.01}$$ is large giving more weight to the total loss. This is in contrast to the uniform weighting $1/n$ that we see with other loss functions.

median = np.median(new_y)
print("Mean of y values: %f"%(mean))
print("Median of y values: %f"%(median))

Mean of y values: 0.943904
Median of y values: 2.813117

The mean value is the best $a_0$ when we use MSE. The median value is the best $a_0$ when we use the MAE. We can see that from the plots above. We can also derive it. (you do not need to have written the following for full credit)

When using MSE, we seek $$\min_{a_0} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i- a_0)^2$$. Take the derivative with respect to $a_0$, set it equal to 0,

$$\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n 2(y_i- a_0)(-1) = 0$$

Cancel the constants, rearrange, and we get $$\sum_{i=1}^n y_i = na_0$$ yeilding the optimal $a_0$ as the mean. (to be rigorous, we should take the second derivative, which is positive, so we are good)

For the median, recall that the absolute value function $f(z) = |z|$ has a derivative of -1 for negative z and +1 for positive z, hence $sign(z)$. When using MAE, we seek $$\min_{a_0} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n |y_i- a_0|$$. Take the derivative with respect to $a_0$, set it equal to 0, and we get $$ -\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n sign(y_i- a_0) = 0$$ Hence, any solution $a_0$ that has an even number of +1 and -1 terms in the summation will be $0$, hence $a_0$ should be above and below an equal number of samples. The median is defined to be that value.

Notice: There appears to be a problem using the LinearRegression library, as it does not always return correct solutions for large $p$. You should get perfect fitting polynomials once $p=n-1$, and for $p>n-1$ there are an infinite number of perfectly fitting solutions (and thus 0 training error). Standardizing the results helps, but this homework was designed in part for you to see the effects of using features in their natural scales.

Since the homework suggested using the LinearRegression library, those results are included here. We expect the training error to flatline at 0, even though the validation error should skyrocket.

#1.(h).ii - fit
train_mse_lst = []

for p in range(1,32):

    poly_reg = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=False).fit(X[:20,:p], Y[:20,:])

    train_hat_y =  poly_reg.predict(X[:20,:p])
    
    train_mse = np.sum((Y[:20,:] - train_hat_y)**2) / len(train_hat_y)
   
    train_mse_lst.append(train_mse)
    
train_mse_arr = np.array(train_mse_lst)

1.(h).iii

Some comments:

-- We see big improvements in the training loss in going from $p=0$ up to $p=3$. After that, it flatlines (future improvements from $p$ to $p+1$ are tiny) for a while before it increases again (we don't expect that part).

-- we should see that the $p=3$ is below the green line (since the ground truth polynomial was an option when the solver was looking for the best cubic function for the training data)

-- We should not see the training error increase (that is a problem with the library)

-- the scale of the MSE is going to be roughly the scale of the square of the length of the range of the y data (about $[0,20]$). So we do expect for the $p=0$ it would be in the low hundreds.

1.(h).v We see that as $p$ increases, the error increases dramatically for large $p$ (most times this script is run). If you zoom in closer (you were not required to do this), you can see that performance fluctuates. Generally, we do expect to see that the validation loss is above the green line. If you re-run the script, sometimes there is improvement initially with increasing $p$, and sometimes there is not.

Regardless of the library used to fit the regression, you should have seen the validation MSE and the ground truth MSE get large as $p$ increased. Pay attention to the scale on the vertical axis. Part of the goal of this exercise was for you to see how even though the training error goes to zero and stays there (which by itself suggests the models are equally good), increasingly high polynomials drastically overfit the data and are terrible for predicting new values.

Some of you correctly guessed it even before implementing that it would be a bad idea to fit 20 data points, drawn from a cubic function, using a 30th degree polynomial. You might not have guessed just how bad it can be. Also, it was easy to forsee that in this example, but much tougher to guess when overfitting might occur with more complex machine learning techniques.

1.(h).vii To evaluate how good a model is, we like to have lots of data not was used for fitting to evaluate the model. In practice, we might only have 10 samples, but here we pretend we have many more. Although it varies each time you re-run the script, we see that generally the 10 sample validation set's curves are fairly similar to those we get with 1000 samples.

1.(h).viii We can solve $$ mse(0) + \lambda*0 = mse(30) + \lambda*30$$ $$\lambda = (mse(0) - mse(30))/30$$ If you got perfect training fit for large $p$, then your $mse(30)=0$

As requested for this problem, the $\lambda$ here is chosen for visualization purposes, though there are some special $\lambda$ values you will use later on.

# fit with all data, keep track of coefficients

train_mse_lst = []
coeff_abs = [] #store sum of abs val of coeff
coeff_sqr = [] #store square of coeff

for p in range(1,32):

    poly_reg = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=False).fit(X[:,:p], Y[:,:])
    print('\nCoefficients for p='+str(p-1))
    print(poly_reg.coef_)
    coeff_abs.append( np.sum( np.abs( poly_reg.coef_) ) )
    coeff_sqr.append( np.sum(  poly_reg.coef_**2 ) )

    train_hat_y =  poly_reg.predict(X[:,:p])
    
    train_mse = np.sum((Y - train_hat_y)**2) / len(train_hat_y)
   
    train_mse_lst.append(train_mse)
    
train_mse_arr = np.array(train_mse_lst)
# print(coeff_abs)

# for penalty p
lamda =(train_mse_arr[0] - train_mse_arr[-1])/30
tot_compl_p= np.array(train_mse_arr) + lamda*np.array(range(31) )

#for penalty sum abs coeff  
lamda =(train_mse_arr[0] - train_mse_arr[-1])/( coeff_abs[-1]-coeff_abs[0]   ) 
# print(lamda)
tot_compl_abs = np.array(train_mse_arr) +lamda*np.array(coeff_abs)

#for penalty sum sqr coeff  
lamda =(train_mse_arr[0] - train_mse_arr[-1])/( coeff_sqr[-1]-coeff_sqr[0]   ) 
tot_compl_sqr = np.array(train_mse_arr) +lamda*np.array(coeff_sqr)

We plotted in red the training error for reference (the total complexity is that red curve plus a line with slope $\lambda$)

Although it varies each time you re-run the script, in many cases there is a V shape to the curve, where there is a quick decrease (where the decreases in training loss dominate), followed by a slow flat increase as the training error is relatively flat and the complexity penalty takes over. In several runs of the script, we found $p=3$ is typically the minimum of the (blue) total complexity curve.

1.(h).ix (discussion) The 30th order model returned using LinearRegression library (in multiple runs of this script) had tiny coefficients, not just for the higher order terms (eg since $x^{30}$ is huge we do expect $a_{30}$ to be small to compensate) but even for the intercept and linear terms. This results in a negative $\lambda$ and bad plots, since the $p=0$ model usually has an $a_0$ usually around 2-5.

In practice for linear regression, the intercept $a_0$ is usually not penalized, so that only the slope is. Having no penalty on $a_0$ also centers the residuals, which is a typical modeling assumption. Since we did not go into depth in lecture on this, the instructions included the penalty on the $a_0$.

There are various relationships that might be of interest. For these plots, it is easier to visually detect relevant features that are continuous valued. For instance, RM seems to be linearly correlated with MEDV, while LSTAT is anti-correlated (larger LSTAT means lower MEDV). LSTAT and MEDV to not seem to have a linear relationship, but a linear model may nonetheless capture the anti-correlation. Generally speaking, the less vertical spread for any point on the horizontal axis (eg for LSTAT=20, MEDV values range from about 5 to 30), the better.

Discrete features can also be quite useful, although it can be tougher to spot potential relationships. ZN seems to be correlated. INDUS seems to be anti-correlated. For the others, it is not as clear from these plots alone.

#(b)  There are a few ways of setting this up
# # The most straightforward is using nested for loops and boolean variables to include (or not) a particular feature
# for includeAGE in [True,False]:
#     for includeINDUS in [True,False]:
#         for includeNOX in [True,False]:
#             ...
#                 trainX = []
#                 if includeAGE:
#                     #append AGE values
#                 if includeINDUS:
#                     #append INDUS values
#                 ...
#                 
#                 #fit
# 
#  # The code below uses a function from the Python library itertools which can be handy
## for larger problems.  

lst_features = ['AGE', 'INDUS', 'NOX', 'RM', 'TAX']
len_comb = len(lst_features)
lst_comb = []
for l in range(1, len_comb+1):
  comb = combinations(lst_features, l) 
  for each in comb:
    lst_comb.append(each)

housing_data_400 = housing_data.head(400)
housing_data_validation = housing_data.tail(100)
housing_fit = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)

mse_train_data = []
mse_val_data = []
housing_reg = housing_fit.fit(np.full(len(housing_data_400['MEDV']), 1).reshape(-1, 1), housing_data_400['MEDV'])
medv_hat_train = housing_reg.predict(np.full(len(housing_data_400['MEDV']), 1).reshape(-1, 1))
mse_train = np.sum((medv_hat_train - housing_data_400['MEDV'])**2)/len(housing_data_400['MEDV'])
mse_train_data.append(['constant', mse_train, 0])

medv_hat_val = housing_reg.predict(np.full(len(housing_data_validation), 1).reshape(-1, 1))
mse_val = np.sum((medv_hat_val - housing_data_validation['MEDV'])**2)/len(housing_data_validation['MEDV'])
mse_val_data.append(['constant', mse_val, 0])


for each in lst_comb:
    housing_reg = housing_fit.fit(housing_data_400[list(each)], housing_data_400['MEDV'])
#     print(housing_reg.coef_, housing_reg.intercept_)
    medv_hat_train = housing_reg.predict(housing_data_400[list(each)])
    mse_train = np.sum((medv_hat_train - housing_data_400['MEDV'])**2)/len(housing_data_400['MEDV'])
    mse_train_data.append([str(list(each)), mse_train, len(list(each))])

    medv_hat_val = housing_reg.predict(housing_data_validation[list(each)])
    mse_val = np.sum((medv_hat_val - housing_data_validation['MEDV'])**2)/len(housing_data_validation['MEDV'])
    mse_val_data.append([list(each), mse_val, len(list(each))])

mse_train_df = pd.DataFrame(mse_train_data, columns=['subset','mse','nmbrfeatures'])
mse_val_df = pd.DataFrame(mse_val_data, columns=['subset','mse','nmbrfeatures'])

print('\n\nHere is the Training MSE')
print(mse_train_df)
print('\n\nHere is the Validation MSE')
print(mse_val_df)

Overall, this choice of $\lambda$ does not heavily penalize the subsets viewed, and we may need to include several more features before we see a visually distinct increase.

2.(c).iv.ii Note: the directions said to let $\lambda$ range from 0 to the same complexity as the $p=0$th model. The $p=0$th model model is what you should get as $\lambda \to \infty$, since all coefficients will be heavily penalized. The goal was to see how performance varies as a function of the $\lambda$, from the regime $\lambda \approx 0$ where the unpenalized, ordinary-least-squares solution is the model, out to the regime $\lambda \to \infty$ where ridge returns the $p=0$ model. In practice, we can select the $\lambda$ with the lowest validation MSE.

The directions did not give guidance about ranging $\lambda$, so we will accept any good-faith effort for this problem. What regime of $\lambda$ will induce changes is data dependent, though since it is trading off training MSE on the one hand and coefficient magnitudes on the other, it will need to be on a scale for those two properties to fight each other.

Below are plots showing a large range of $\lambda$ values, using a log-log plot to show a large range.

Here, some of the coefficients are small, and the coefficient for NOX is set to exactly 0. So Lasso appears to have found a sparser model than Ridge did, although still not as sparse as the model with Mallow's Cp. Recall that penalizing the number of non-zero coefficients is the strictest type of penalty; Ridge allows all the coefficients to remain if they are sufficiently small. Lasso is in between.

2.(c).iv.v For Mallow's Cp, which only counts the number of non-zero coefficients (no matter how big or small), it does not matter. We would get the same linear relationship; the coefficients would adjust to a revised scale.

For Lasso and Ridge regression, which penalize the magnitudes of the coefficients, whether we normalize (to $[0,1]$) or standardize (subtract mean and divide by standard deviation) will affect the coefficient magnitudes and consequently how big the penalty is for a particular model. It certainly is possible that if we changed the scales (standardizing or just measuring in different units), that would effect which model got picked in the end.

In the future, we will usually standardize, but one goal of this homework was for you to think a little about coefficient magnitudes, how they relate to (diverse) feature scales, and if/when that might affect machine learning procedures.

housing_fit = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True) #when we fit, just pass in features, no need column of ones
p = 1
while len( lst_features_remain ) >0:
    
    bestfeat = None
    bestmse = 10**8
    
    for feat in lst_features_remain:
        
        Xtrain = housing_data_400[ lst_features_added + [feat] ]
        Ytrain = housing_data_400['MEDV']
        
        Xval = housing_data_validation[ lst_features_added + [feat] ]
        Yval = housing_data_validation['MEDV']
        
        housing_reg = housing_fit.fit( Xtrain, Ytrain )
        
        medv_hat_train = housing_reg.predict(Xtrain)
        mse_train = np.sum((medv_hat_train - Ytrain)**2)/len(Ytrain)        
        
        medv_hat_val = housing_reg.predict(Xval)
        mse_val = np.sum((medv_hat_val - Yval)**2)/len(Yval)

        print((p,feat,mse_val))
        
        if mse_val < bestmse:
            bestmse = mse_val
            bestfeat = feat
            
            print('updating with '+feat)
            
    for_steps.append( (p,bestfeat,bestmse,mse_train) )
    p += 1
    lst_features_remain.remove(bestfeat)
    lst_features_added.append(bestfeat)

In [45]:
housing_fit = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True) #when we fit, just pass in features, no need column of ones
p = len( lst_features_remain )
while len( lst_features_remain ) >1:
    
    worstfeat = None  #the worst feature is the one that reduces the mse the least
    bestmse = 10**8
    
    for feat in lst_features_remain:
        
        #create a copy without feat
        lst_tmp = list(lst_features_remain)
        lst_tmp.remove(feat)
        
        Xtrain = housing_data_400[ lst_tmp ]
        Ytrain = housing_data_400['MEDV']
        
        Xval = housing_data_validation[ lst_tmp ]
        Yval = housing_data_validation['MEDV']
        
        housing_reg = housing_fit.fit( Xtrain, Ytrain )
               
        medv_hat_train = housing_reg.predict(Xtrain)
        mse_train = np.sum((medv_hat_train - Ytrain)**2)/len(Ytrain)        
        
        medv_hat_val = housing_reg.predict(Xval)
        mse_val = np.sum((medv_hat_val - Yval)**2)/len(Yval)

        print((p,feat,mse_val))
        
        if mse_val < bestmse:
            bestmse = mse_val
            worstfeat = feat
            
            print('updating with '+feat)
            
    back_steps.append( (p,worstfeat,bestmse,mse_train) )
    p -= 1
    lst_features_remain.remove(worstfeat)

    
#do fit for the last remaining feature
Xtrain = housing_data_400[ lst_features_remain ]
Ytrain = housing_data_400['MEDV']

Xval = housing_data_validation[ lst_features_remain ]

2.(d).iii The sequence of models is quite distinct. If we lay out the nesting with $p=1$ first from both searches, we get

Forward search: 'LSTAT' 'PTRATIO' 'CHAS' 'ZN' 'INDUS' 'TAX' 'NOX' 'DIS' 'CRIM' 'AGE''B' 'RAD' 'RM'

Backward search: 'PTRATIO' 'NOX' 'B' 'RAD' 'LSTAT' 'DIS' 'CHAS' 'INDUS' 'ZN' 'CRIM' 'AGE' 'TAX' 'RM'

The most obvious similarity is that PRATIO is included in almost all the models, and RM is the least helpful feature (we discussed why above). We also see features like 'AGE' and 'CRIM' are only included in the larger models (so generally speaking not as helpful).

But other features get added/removed in quite different places. For instance, 'NOX' is the second to last feature to be removed with backward search, but is the the 6th feature to be added in forward. 'B' and 'RAD' are the third to last and second to last to be added in forward search, while they were among the final four features in backward search.

# Ridge
lst_features = list(housing_data.columns)
lst_features.remove('MEDV')
ridge_plot_x = []
ridge_plot_valmse = []
ridge_plot_valcomp = []
ridge_plot_trainmse = []
ridge_plot_traincomp = []

lambdas = [10**i for i in np.linspace(-10,+20,1000)]

Xtrain = housing_data_400[ lst_features ]
Ytrain = housing_data_400['MEDV']

Xval = housing_data_validation[ lst_features ]
Yval = housing_data_validation['MEDV']


for lamda in lambdas: 

    ridge_reg = Ridge(alpha=lamda, fit_intercept=True).fit(Xtrain, Ytrain)
    
    ridge_train_hat = ridge_reg.predict( Xtrain )
    ridge_mse_train = np.sum((Ytrain - ridge_train_hat)**2)/len(Ytrain)
    ridge_train_complexity = ridge_mse_train + lamda * np.sum(ridge_reg.coef_[0:]**2)
    ridge_plot_traincomp.append(ridge_train_complexity)
    ridge_plot_trainmse.append(ridge_mse_train)    
    
    ridge_val_hat = ridge_reg.predict( Xval )
    ridge_mse_val = np.sum(( Yval - ridge_val_hat)**2)/len(Yval)
    ridge_val_complexity = ridge_mse_val + lamda * np.sum(ridge_reg.coef_[0:]**2)
    ridge_plot_valcomp.append(ridge_val_complexity)
    ridge_plot_valmse.append(ridge_mse_val)
    
# minimizer
argmin = ridge_plot_valmse.index( min(ridge_plot_valmse) )
print('Minimizing lambda, valMSE, and coeff are ')
print(lambdas[argmin])
print(ridge_plot_valmse[argmin])

#refit to get the coeff for the best model
ridge_reg = Ridge(alpha=lambdas[argmin], fit_intercept=True).fit(Xtrain, Ytrain)
for i in range(len(lst_features)):
    print('%6s\t%.4e'%(lst_features[i], ridge_reg.coef_[i]))

Using LASSO on all features, we see many coefficients are set to 0, such as CRIM, INDUS, CHAS, and several others. This is in stark contrast to the model found with Ridge regression. The only features that have non-zero coefficients in the Lasso model are

ZN, AGE, TAX, B, and LSTAT,

and that set (for the particular coefficients chosen) have validation MSE of 15.8. Interestingly, these variables do not quite align closely with either Backward or Forward searches.

For instance, similar to forward search, LASSO keeps LSTAT, but LASSO also keeps AGE and B which forward search only included at the end.

Similar to backward search, LASSO included B, LSTAT, ZN; however, LASSO also kept AGE and TAX among its small set of features while backward search discarded those early on.
